        <h3>Acquisition of literature on the study of religion <b>:: Monographic Literature</b></h3>
        <p>The FID acquires monographs and collected works from Germany and abroad according to a profile agreed with the specialist community. The profile primarily comprises literature on:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Theory, methodology, history and comparison of religions</li>
            <li>
                Religions in the international and global context, especially New Religious Movements.<br/>
                <i>Please note:</i> Literature on individual non-Christian religions is collected in the respective Regional Studies’ FID, e.g. FID "Near and Middle East, Islamic Studies"; FID CrossAsia; FID Jewish Studies and is therefore acquired by FID Religious Studies only by exception.
            </li>
            <li>Spiritual movements of any kind: pseudo-, anti-, non-religions; atheism and ‘Religionskritik’.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Pro-active and patron-driven acquisition</h4>
        <p>In addition to the pro-active acquisition by the subject specialist, there are two components of a user-controlled acquisition:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>By a PDA component included in <b>RelBib</b>, the Bibliography of the study of religion, users can trigger acquisitions of titles that are indexed but so far not accessible anywhere in Germany.</li>
            <li>In addition, there is the possibility of proposing titles of any format of interest to the study of religion, which are not (yet) listed in RelBib and therefore cannot be ordered via the PDA function mentioned above.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>With these three strategic acquisition components, FID Religionswissenschaft hopes to meet the demand for a comprehensive information and supply of literature in the field of the study of religion.</p>


        <h3>Acquisition of Study of Religion Literature <b>:: Journals</b></h3>
        <p>A definition of what exactly a “Study of Religion journal” is or, providing a list of journals relevant to the study of religion proves to be extremely difficult. The answer may vary between individual academics depending on their specialization.</p>
        <p>The ‘FID Study of Religion’ has currently subscribed to or licensed 193 journals, some of which are also included in interdisciplinary 'packages'. Many of the journals have already been held at the library as part of the former SSG programme. Approximately 20 journals are owned exclusively by Tübingen university library.</p>
        <p>Considering the varying specialization possible in the field of the study of religion, it becomes clear that there are important journals which may belong to neighbouring subjects, such as journals on individual religions, also Christianity, journals in the social, cultural and regional sciences, history and many other subjects even up to medicine and natural sciences.</p>
        <p>Bearing this in mind, it becomes clear that in addition to a well-founded acquisition profile, the indexing of relevant (journal) literature in the field of the study of religion plays an important, if not the most important, role.</p>


        <h4>RelBib – Bibliography of the Study of Religion and more</h4>
        <p>The focus of the ‘FID Study of Religion’ lies on the <a href="<?=$this->url('content-page', ['page' => 'about_relbib'])?>">reation, continuation and improvement of <b>RelBib</b></a>. This comprehensive bibliography of literature relevant to the study of religion was released on 24 July 2017 in an alpha version and has been published in June 2019 in the current portal environment, in which all information and services for the study of religion community are offered under one interface.</p>
